· ing years into a strong and abiding attachment. Atticus inher- iting great wealth and preferring a life of refinement and leisure ,

to the cares of public office,'withdrew from the turmoil and danger consequent upon the unsettled condition of the Roman state, and resided for many years in Greece. This gave him abundant opportunity to pursue his studies and to try his hand as publisher, author, and literary critic, in the last of which rdles, especially, he displayed talent of no mean order.
